[4] Simple Addition¶

[5] Let us first try adding the following single channel images together:

In [2]:
#[6]

img1 = cv2.imread("Images/bwdiagonal.jpg")  
img2 = cv2.imread("Images/white.jpg")

mat1 = np.asmatrix(img1[:,:,0])
mat2 = np.asmatrix(img2[:,:,0])

mat3 = mat1+mat2

plt.imshow(mat3[:,:],cmap='gray')
Out[2]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x722a58391ca0>

[7] The above code did simple matrix addition. Some elements in the the final sum may exceed 255 which is the maximum value for intensity for an image. OpenCV deals with this by classifying all values greater than 255 as maximum intensity.

For example, if elements add up to 321, the pixel with have same intensity as 255.

In short, all pixels with values greater than 255 are pure white. This may lead to loss in detail in the resultant image

Let us define a function to add images:

In [5]:
#[9]

def PicSum(x,y): 
    matx = np.asmatrix(x[:,:,0])
    matx = (1/255)*matx
    maty = np.asmatrix(y[:,:,0])
    maty = (1/255)*maty

    matxy = matx + maty
    matxy = 255*matxy

    return(plt.imshow(matxy,cmap='gray'))

[11] Weighted Addition¶

[12] We shall use the following formula to do weighted addition of images:

I = α × A + (1 − α) × B

Where I is the final image matrix, and A, B are the input image matrices. α is the parameter which will control weight of an image.

In [7]:
#[13]

def W_add(p,q,k): 
    return( k*p + (1-k)*q)

def W_PicSum(x,y,t=0.5):
    matx = np.asmatrix(x[:,:,0])
    matx = (1/255)*matx
    maty = np.asmatrix(y[:,:,0])
    maty = (1/255)*maty

    matxy = W_add(matx, maty, t)
    matxy = 255*matxy

    return(plt.imshow(matxy,cmap='gray'))
